## 2. Start each major session with an explicit instruction
In Claude Code, begin with something like:

```text
Before doing anything else, read and obey these docs:

- .claude/CLAUDE.md
- docs/ARCHITECTURE.md
- docs/MVP_SPEC.md
- docs/RISKS_AND_PLAN.md
- docs/SPIKES_PHASE0.md

They are the project constitution. If any future request conflicts with them,
you must warn me and prefer the docs over my ad‑hoc request.

For this session, your job is: [planning / implementing slice X / running spike Y].
Do not modify these docs unless I explicitly ask.
```

This tells Claude to treat them as hard constraints, not just context.

## 3. When you narrow scope, re-point it
For a specific task, remind it of **which subset** applies:

```text
For this task, the relevant docs are:

- .claude/CLAUDE.md
- docs/ARCHITECTURE.md
- docs/MVP_SPEC.md (Record + Edit sections)
- docs/SPIKES_PHASE0.md (Spike 1)

Re-summarize in your own words the constraints that affect this task,
then propose a plan, then implement.
```

Having Claude restate the constraints makes it less likely to drift.

## 4. Enforce “warn on conflict”
Always include a line like:

```text
If my request ever conflicts with these docs, stop and explain the conflict
instead of silently following my request.
```

That makes the spec the source of truth, not your latest message.

## 5. Use fresh sessions for big context shifts
For big milestones (e.g., after spikes, before Phase 1), open a new Claude Code session and re-attach the same core docs as the starting message, with a short “what changed” note. This keeps context clean instead of relying on long chat history. [code.claude](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/best-practices)

